				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The MMC5 is still a bit of a mystery, and AFAIK it hasn't been fully replicated yet. Support for it in popular Flash Carts (PowerPak and Everdrive N8) is partial. It would also be significantly more expensive to include in production carts than AxROM or UxROM for example, since an FPGA that can host the MMC5 costs tens of dollar (I think) while the simple logic chips for the discrete mappers cost dimes.<br /><br />Over the years I've grown fond of the simplest discrete logic mappers. They don't give you anything more than access to more PRG-ROM, but in most cases that's all you'll need. With CHR-RAM you can pull off a lot of interesting tricks, and by dynamically updating parts of it (a rudimentary form of simulating CHR bankswitching) you can show very diverse graphics throughout each level.<br /><br />Sure, scanline counters, 8KB of extra RAM and fine CHR bankswitching all sound like awesome features to have available, but the difficulty and cost they add to producing carts is hardly worth it, IMO.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">you can always create your own mapper to suit your needs.</div><br />But you'll also have to make your own emulator or modify an existing one to support your new mapper, otherwise you won't be able to test your ROM. You'll also need to understand at least the very basics of electronics in order to design something feasible.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

