				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sat Feb 12, 2005 9:43 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 6693<br /><b>Location:</b> Rio de Janeiro - Brazil
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">One of the biggest complicating things about the MMC5 is that it provides so much versatility when any given game will most likely only use one of them. (four different PRG banking modes? six different CHR banking modes? all the things the extra 1KiB RAM can be used for? ) Which is why I've personally been recommending &quot;(talk to people to help you) pick a subset of the MMC5 if you want something that the MMC3 doesn't provide&quot;, because it gets the cart out from under the horse.</div><br />That's good advice, but things are complicated when you have to depend on someone else for periods as long as the development cycle of a (big) game.<br /><br />Say you're looking the mapper you'll use in the game you plan to release on actual carts. You will not begin programming for a mapper until you find someone who is willing to supply the physical mapper, but once you do find a supplier, it will be a while until the game is ready to be put on cartridges, and in the mean time something can go wrong (the supplier abandons the community or whatever), and you're screwed. Restricting yourself to the simple mappers ensures that the cartridges will be easy to manufacture when the time comes, no matter who does it.<br /><br />This is the reason I prefer to stick to simple mappers. I can't make any commitment to have the software ready by a certain date, and I don't want to risk not being able to manufacture cartridges when I do finish the software. The only way I'd use a complex mapper was if I had a significant number of boards with me since the beginning of development, or if I had the hardware knowledge to produce the mapper myself, so I wouldn't have to depend on anyone else.</div>

